   <abstract >This study focuses on the domestic activities of middle Republican colonies, that iscolonies of the 3rd to 1st centuries BCE, including those of non-elite households, to understand the regional adaptations to the environment and its effects on house design and household behavior, with a specific focus on water. The archaeological data collected reveal the variety of ways in which the construction and domestic practices of Roman colonies adapted water management practices to new environments. The results of this analysis elucidate elements of the daily life of middle Roman colonists across the Italian peninsula, an area and period with comparatively low resolution in scholarship outside of the Bay of Naples. This project fills the lacuna by presenting a series of case studies that preserve piecemeal evidence of the domestic sphere during the pivotal period of Roman development on the Italian peninsula in the 3rd to 1st centuries BCE. This study investigates responses to variations in regional and local ecologies to analyze how adaptations to local environment shaped divergent architecture of domestic spaces in different localized environments of Italy. I analyze practices of harvesting rainwater in the domestic sphere at the microscale—at the level of individual houses—as well as at the macroscale--the regional level of the Italian peninsula--drawing on recent approaches in the field of household archaeology and on behavior-focused theories, including Bourdieu's practice theory. This multiscalar analysis facilitates broader comparisons of individual and societal responses to resource management and house design in the context of the local environment with a focus on the households of central Italian Roman colonies in the middle Republican period.</abstract>
